article.description: Vanderbilt (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) proved that it can win without Chantelle Anderson. Sort of.
article.headline: Vandy pulls together after Anderson fouls out early
article.linkText: Anderson fouls out early, but Vandy gets by Syracuse
article.story:
SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Vanderbilt (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) proved that it can win without Chantelle Anderson. Sort of.

	   Anderson played only 16 minutes Tuesday night before fouling out
for the 21st time in her stellar career. But Jenni Benningfield
made up for her absence with 19 points and eight rebounds, and
Hillary Hager and Ashley Earley combined for 21 points as the
Commodores survived a late Syracuse rally and held on for a 73-65
victory.

	   ''When Chantelle went out, I knew everybody had to step up
because the roles change a little bit,'' said Benningfield, who
also had two blocks and two steals. ''We just had to come out and
execute the things we know how to do without Chantelle. We had
spurts where we executed and there were spurts we didn't. Until we
play a 40-minute game, we obviously cannot be satisfied.''

	   The 6-foot-6 Anderson, SEC player of the year, was in foul
trouble early, and her prolonged absence allowed the Orangewomen
(0-3) to stay in the game against the bigger Commodores (2-0).

	   Four of Anderson's fouls were offensive. She was called for her
first infraction just 22 seconds into the game, received her third
with 6:11 left in the first half, and fouled out with 2:10
remaining in the game. She also received a technical after the
fifth.

	   ''I think everybody could see that I was frustrated,'' said
Anderson, who scored 11 points, seven of them in the first five
minutes of the game. ''It's frustrating when you're used to playing
35 minutes a game and you only play 16. For 16 minutes I was pretty
effective, but I wasn't allowed to play.''

	   Tierra Jackson led Syracuse with 16 points and 11 rebounds.
Julie McBride finished with 15 points and Rochelle Coleman had 12
for the Orangewomen, who had 17 offensive rebounds to 13 for Vandy
and forced 20 turnovers.

	   When Anderson, who repeatedly was double- and triple-teamed, was
called for her fourth foul with 15:31 to go, Vandy led 48-34.
Benningfield responded by hitting consecutive baskets in a
50-second span, and Abi Ramsey and Ashley McElhiney, who had 11
assists, each hit 3-pointers to keep the Commodores comfortably in
front, 58-47 with 8:18 left.

	   A 3-pointer by McBride and two baskets from Shannon Perry moved
Syracuse within 66-59 only seconds before Anderson fouled out.

	   When that fifth foul came, Anderson's frustration led to the
technical, and McBride converted the two free throws. And when
Perry hit a driving layup through the lane with 1:59 to go, the
lead was down to 66-63.

	   But Earley converted a three-point play to halt the Syracuse
rally and the Orangewomen ran out of time.

	   ''We put ourselves in position to win,'' Syracuse coach Marianna
Freeman said. ''What has hurt us in these three games is lack of
experience. But in each game we have played better. We just made
more mistakes than we could afford tonight. I think my team is
getting better every game. Now they understand what it's like to
play a ranked team.''

	   Anderson, accustomed to dominating inside, scored seven of the
Commodores' first 12 points. A bank shot by Benningfield and a
steal and courtlong rush and layup by Tia Battle staked Vandy t o a
26-15 lead at 8:39.

	   Without Anderson's presence in the lane, however, Syracuse
quickly took advantage, going on a 13-2 run. Jackson, who had five
points in the spurt, hit a layup with 2:13 left to move Syracuse
within 30-28. The Vanderbilt bench was hit with a technical after
the play and McBride converted the two free throws to tie the
score.

	   Benningfield's layup off an inbounds pass gave Vandy a 37-34
halftime lead.

	   When Syracuse failed to score on its first nine possessions of
the second half, the Commodores appeared set to run away to a rout.
Anderson's jumper in the lane boosted the lead to 48-34 with 16:01
left, but her fourth foul came just 30 seconds later.
